{
  "doc_id": "21503",
  "text": "This indicates a high risk of extinction for endangered populations as has been stated for the Amur tigers (Panthera tigris altaica) [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] and for the Giant pandas (Ailuropoda melanoleuca) [CITATION_3] ; in these populations, recent outbreaks of CDV have become an important cofactor in reducing free-ranging wildlife animals and even in a few breeding centers, demonstrating the need to implement mitigation strategies such as vaccination or antivirals to reduce the heavy impact of this infection on those populations [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] It is important to highlight that periodic serological and molecular evaluations, and an active search for possible wildlife reservoirs of CDV could help prevent outbreaks of diseases in other susceptible wildlife [CITATION_7] , and that domestic dogs, mesocarnivores or peridomestic wild animals (not only carnivores) should be taken into account as possible sources of CDV infections in wildlife [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] . The wide variety of possible hosts for CDV that we were able to find, agrees with recent papers showing that domestic dogs are not the only potential reservoir of CDV.",
